text: Remember when people actually had original ideas for movies, rather than "Lets take this franchise and remodel it, but with minority groups and women instead of men!" (In this instance, race isn't a real factor, Oceans 11 featured Caucasian, Asian, and African "protagonists" if you want to call them that, and the representation of the overall atmosphere the movie represents is spot on. I mainly mean a reference to things like the new Teen Titans Live action skit that's in the works-https://cdn.discordapp.com/attachments/359579711900221441/433795886242463744/Andyouthoughtteentitansgowasbad_1e4d2e_6575457.png). While it is true the movie is "different" in what they're trying to steal, and the actresses are talented in their own right,  it, calling it now, is likely to run directly into the exact same problem the Ghost-busters she-make did, that being: What the **** is the point?   Now, if you were to take this same cast, and put these women into a movie that isn't a "Progressive Remodel" of a perfectly good franchise, that could be quite the film, if it's done properly! Maybe, I don't know, a generic fantasy setting! Or, (and I can't believe I'm suggesting this for how overplayed the ideal has been since GG), a group of women who get into an online game (maybe an mmo?) together! There is NO need any of this Social Justice shit to have to be strung out and portrayed EVERYWHERE it can get light! Lets all of us stop accepting these shitty excuses for an equality movement that is modern day "Social Justice", and call it out for the shameless shit it is when there's a Oxygen Copy of something that already exists, just more progressive!

text: Phenomenally talented cast, but this movie is cheapened by riding the coattails of an established franchise that was male-centric.  It's crafty of studios to try and mitigate risk by rehashing established brands, but the blowback from people who see through this blatant cash grabbing is deserved.  Give these ladies the respect they deserve and put them in a NEW franchise instead of retconning them into established fiction.  I won't say this is Ghostbusters 2.0 because this trailer doesn't make me cringe the way the Ghostbusters trailer did, but this is just the latest in the growing trend of Hollywood being unoriginal and trying to repackage and resell us our nostalgia in the pursuit of safe money.

text: Dear Hollywood:  - Stop rebooting old franchises and start making new ones. More recently "Jumanji" comes to mind.  - Stop taking movies with an all male cast and replacing them with females, then slapping a franchise name on the title in name of "women's equality".   If you really want to show that women can act just as well as men, then make an original film that is just as good as "Ocean's 11" or "Ghostbusters". They shouldn't need that "franchise boost", if they're truly great movies.  Hollywood for the most part is being lazy and if anything is doing a disservice to the cause of "women's equality" by making such tasteless films. I honestly do not care if the cast is all male, or female, actors. We've seen time and time again that both genders can act just as well as the other. Just start making original movies, and stop rehashing the same stuff each year. It'd also be nice if the inclusion of political toxicity would stop in most every film that is pushed out. That's doing nothing other than facilitating the already toxic environment that persists.

text: The thing I don‚Äôt get is why it‚Äôs a remake. Don‚Äôt get me wrong I love all of these women, I think they‚Äôre all amazing, and I honestly love the idea of an all-female heist movie - my only gripe with this movie is that they didn‚Äôt change the plot. Why does it have to be a remake? Why can‚Äôt it be part of the Ocean‚Äôs series but have an original plot? I‚Äôm sure when this movie comes out, the acting will be great, the camerawork will be great, the set will be great, but the plot will be the downfall of this movie, because it has been done before. I swear if they‚Äôd just changed the plot I would be so excited for this but I know this won‚Äôt be too enjoyable because I‚Äôve basically already seen a pretty awesome rendition of the same story. This is the reason why there is always backlash when it‚Äôs an all-female remake, not because sexism, because the original movie is so great to begin with it doesn‚Äôt need a remake. text: Can we make it a point to bring attention to the fact that the people producing this movie are creating yet another classic movie sequel with a primarily female cast made up of big names that are presumably going to be in no significant way a fitting choice for their roles in the story? I don't know about how anyone else feels, but I'm going to start telling people to boycott these types of soulless movies that blatantly prey on people's morals or interests and trick them into giving away their money for something that isn't enjoyable. I wish more people had the tenacity to stand up to these "blockbuster" film tyrants so that we would have more space in theatres for films that has actual content, or even better, finally start supporting our amateur and prospective cinematographers. It's never a bad time to start, and it isn't impossible to take on these goliath companies and see a new moviescape one day, one filled with original ideas and insightful interpretations.

text: I'm not sure making the female equivalent to Ocean's 11 is really that conducive to breaking female stereotypes or at all empowering for women. Why not do something original with an all female cast? (Most likely because studios will not invest, but still). All this film is saying is, "Hey! Look! We can do the same things the guys can!", it's such a patronising statement to be saying to women and a VERY cynical move on the studio's behalf. The focus of Ocean's 11 was never the fact they were all men whereas the entire point of this film is that all the characters are women, which gives the impression that there's not much more to them besides their gender. Women shouldn't be aspiring to fill the shoes of the men who previously wore them, they ought to wear their own shoes and make their mark.

text: I have absolutely no problem with films that have strong female leads, in fact some of my favourite films have female as the main protagonist eg La Femme Nikita, The Fifth Element, Underworld, Alien etc.  However when you target films that already have a huge fan base and start pushing an agenda (like have an all female cast for no reason) then you have to expect a backlash.   In this progressive era if you dare to make a film that stars ONLY white men, then you are asking for trouble.  This is the blatant double standard, on the one hand an all female cast is seen as empowering for women (cough bullshit cough)and on the other, having a cast of only white men would probably be considered promoting white supremacy and somehow encouraging hatred and violence against women.  I am not kidding, as you can always rely of sjw dipshits and feminists to do all sorts of mental gymnastics to arrive at ridiculous conclusions.  If the goal is equal representation, then the obvious questions that one might ask is; Why do we need equal representation? Where do we draw the line?  For example, I could say that there are not enough Peter Dinklages in the film industry.  So lets starting promoting equal representation for little people.  Lets target films that had an impact on film history like Blade Runner, The Terminator, Alien, Total Recall and Back to the Future etc.  Then lets remake those films where the leads roles are all replaced with little people.  What about sick/ disabled people.  Lets find any film that stars healthy actors and replace them all with actors that are blind, deaf, who have Asperger's, or who is Autistic, who are missing limbs etc.  What about old people?  Lets target a film (like American Pie) that stars young actors and replace them with geriatrics. I could go on, but hopefully you get my point.

text: I'd just like to point out that not once in the trailer was a single feminist thing done or said, no one made any "girl power" jokes, no one did any "man hating" things, it's just a fucking action heist movie. That's it. You all made it about feminism and gender and male vs female, not the movie trailer.   Anyone assuming the film was made for some sort of agenda past just milking the Ocean's series, or who is hating on it purely because there are a lot of women starring in it, needs to re-examine themselves because y'all have some sexism that's deep rooted. If the first and only thing you noticed about the trailer was that there are primarily women and you have a problem with that then maybe the problem isn't the movie.   I've never been into the Ocean's movies and I agree, it'd be cooler to see something original. But if they MUST make more of them, it's nice to see they're at least switching up who they're casting for the lead roles. It could be good, it could be bad. But some of y'all are judging it super harshly just based off the trailer and purely because there are a lot of women in it. Some of you judging are probably some of the same people who get angry when "liberal snowflakes" talk about how they don't like how so many movies have all male leads. So really just look at yourself, look at your choices, and stop being so damn sensitive. It's a movie for fucks sake.

text: Ocean's 8 is another gender politics propaganda film riding the coattails of a successful masculine film franchise. I came up with a better Ocean's film idea and it took less than 5 minutes.  Years after the adventures of the heist team everyone is living well. One day Danny Ocean is murdered and Tess and Danny's son and daughter are kidnapped. The kidnappers happen to be old business associates Danny had and through flashbacks we see why Danny was murdered.  The kidnappers are demanding a large amount of gold and other extremely hard to obtain assets they have been wanting. The problem is the items the kidnappers want are constantly being moved and the time window to obtain all the items is limited. Tess has only 48 hours to complete the tasks in order to save her son and daughter.  Tess realizes she must reassemble the team along with some new members.  The heist team will consist of both women and men. The heist team will travel the world where they will face some of the most challenging tasks they have ever faced. In the film a touching tribute is made to Frank Catton who was portrayed by Bernie Mac.  Through the film we learn more about Danny Ocean and his relationship with Tess. In the film Tess discovers that Danny has left a message that explains who the kidnappers are and that they never keep their word. The heist team will have to find a way to keep Tess's children alive by stealing the necessary items, and the heist team must steal the children from the kidnappers too. The film leaves the possibility of a new trilogy open filled with new exciting characters.
author: David Smith

text: So this is my personal opinion but why such the hate? I understand the context where the orginal Ocean's 8 was orginally a predominant male cast geared specifcally to male audiences and is held as a nolsagic memory for many. But what I am reading thus far is that the hate directed at this reboot is the anger of the gender reversal and how is supposedly is not empowering and "piggybanks" on male success. Which, in theory, I do agree as in film - and especially in Hollywood - we need more female centered orginal plots that tell its own story with its own complexities. And although I would be the first to say that Hollywood is exceptional at snubbing female - especially women of color - characters needed development and instead reduces them to token prizes or eye candy directed specifcally for male eyes, I personally do see this as development. I have so far read the problem that is constantly being addressed - about the apperently uneeded women reboot - the context of the said problem is often ignored. No offense to the men that were saying that this isn't  empowering - which to extent you are right, and I am sure Hollywood is not going to give these women the justice they truly deserve - but throughout film industry, the only roles that women were allowed were an object or were ignored if they were within screenplay/editing. And in a movie world where media is such an influential tool - more in modern times than ever - it is even all that more important to see yourself in a hero or main character that looks like you; regardless who you are. And so, if you are a cis, white, heterosexual male - you will typically see a hero/villain/character who looks like you on screen, an aspect that has been true since the start of the film's origins within a segregated society. Sure now, we have gotten a bit better. But obviously it is still not enough. Look at the comments below, with - typically - men saying "[Women] have ruined The Last Jedi" and "Marvel is safe for now" all refering to the supposed negative connotations that come with increase involvement of women in francshise that were orginally geared towards men in an obviously unfair and sexist bias. All in all, though I do wish for more original female centered narratives that do not rely on popular franchises, I do believe, however, that this is nonetheless progress as it broadens the roles that women were comfined to. And besides, Hollywood has been doing so many reboots of franchises - good and bad - in a large variety of genres that do have mostly male casts, and this has not yet convinced many that men should not be involved in reboots. So why then does the game change when there is a reboot with a mostly female cast in worlds where it would not be implausable for there to be an all women team? Sure this reboot may be bad, but why should that indicate a supposed pattern that an all female cast reboots will always be bad? And so as a woman that always had to sit through interesting storylines, complex world, with virtually no women or women that were only used as a glorfoed sex doll who's emotional complexity is near to nothing, I can say that this is a nice change of pace is progress no matter how much I may like it. For once fellas, you may see the roles reversed and see that women getting a foot doesnt knock a foot off your mile. This concludes my opinion and I am open to any discussion but only in a civil manner. Thank you.

text: SPOILERS: I was excited about this and it was fun, but it wasn't great fun. I think they played it safe to ensure a good start to what will hopefully be an on-going franchise. The best parts in my opinion, were Cate Blanchett's "Lou" character and Anne Hathaway's "Daphne Kluger" character, who stole the show and had the most laughs. They payed homage to Ocean's 11, which I liked, but it also forced me to make comparisons between this and Ocean's 11, which made me like this less. This heist wasn't as crisp and tight as Danny's casino heist. The characters weren't as starkly outlined in this as the 11 were--and Ocean's 8 has some great characters too. They could've played that up more. They reused Yen, the acrobat, which I thought was a cop-out. They couldn't find a lady acrobat? Maybe they just wanted him to make an appearance, but to me it made the heist feel sloppier. Yen should also get a cut of the money right? Do the other Ocean's 8 members know? It was never mentioned. And then Daphne Kluger also gets a cut? Was that planned? Maybe? 6 of the 8 Ocean's crew members didn't even know about the majority of the jewels that ended up being stolen. Did Sandra Bullock just let them in on it out of good will? "Weee! We're rich out of nowhere!" I guess. Then at the end, Sandra Bullock gives her "dead" brother a toast and says "you would've loved it." To me this takes away from the new Ocean's crew. I don't know. There were many slight changes they could've made that would've made this a tighter, more fun, more successful movie.

text: Saw it now and I gotta say it isnt bad. Its just nothing you would watch a second time. I dont see the point in raging against this, because it isnt bad enough to be raging. Story is just of medium quality compared to what we are used to these days. It might have been a success 10 or 15 years ago. But how do you make a better movie in a franchise? you have to maintain the idea while keeping the viewers excited with "harder, faster, smarter" scenes. Obviously you will fail at some point. Like Fast n Furious and Transformers did. Cars falling/flyn in the sky and 50 explosions in 3 seconds. What would that mean for Oceans? How much more complicated and sneaky can you make it before most of the viewers simply wont be able to follow anymore?  Id rather aks two questions:  1. why was it necessary to do an all female (or all men) cast? why not just mix it, what would have been the problem with that? The world is full with men AND women. 2. If you decide to make or participate in a franchise movie, why not wait for a script that actually has the potential to be better than the ones before? why do they keep coming up with movies that are clearly not gonna be successes?  I repeat: to me Oceans 8 was not a bad movie, but it clearly failed on too many levels to ever become a success. So no need to blame anyone or anything except for those who made it, caus this was at no point "close" to being a good movie. Professionals would have seen that coming! they made it anyway...
